found in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Barwick","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Berwick or Barwick, for example in Northumberland, Norfolk, Somerset, and Yorkshire, from Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying farm building’, i.e. a granary lying some distance away from the main settlement.","North German: habitational name from a place called Berwick, near Soest, in Westphalia."]}]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Andrew Barton was born in 1420, in Edinburgh, Scotland, his father, William Barton, was 30 and his mother, Agnes Turnbull, was 25. He married Margaret Prestoun in 1442, in Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died on 2 July 1518, in Edinburgh, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 98."},"et":{"1420–2 July 1518":"1420–2. juuli 1518","1420–1518":"1420–1518","1423–1455":"1423–1455","1434–1476":"1434–1476","1440–1476":"1440–1476","–Male":"Surnud","1390–1425":"1390–1425","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","2 July 1518":"2. juuli 1518","1440":"1440","1395":"1395","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1434":"1434","1423":"1423